<font color="#FF0000">ONE PROTESTER'S STORY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Mar 12 22:43:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
First of all, I would like to commend the Vietnam vets.  You did your duty and all Americans owe you their appreciation. The fact that the war was a horrific mistake in no way diminishes the sacrifices that you made.<br><br>
As for me, I was a protester against the war.  Oh, not a really active protester but a protester none the less.  I do not doubt that there were individuals who called themselves<br>
anti-war protesters who spat on and otherwise insulted Vietnam veterans.  As far as I am concerned that behavior was beneath contempt.  The vast majority of protesters such as myself were motivated by a patriotic desire to get our country out of that mess and to save our fighting men from dying and suffering in vain.<br><br>
On a Saturday in April 1967, almost exactly 30 years ago, I participated the great peace march that took place in San Francisco.  The mood was one of patriotism; the Stars and<br>
Stripes flew everywhere in that immense crowd.  I remember there was a U.S. Navy sailor in uniform participating in the march.  He wore a long raincoat to conceal it but those of us around him knew and thanked him.  I imagine he took part at considerable risk to himself.<br><br>
Why was I a protester?  I took it upon myself to find out as much about Vietnam as I could.  I learned about the ancient struggles of the Vietnamese against the Chinese and more recently against the French.  I became convinced that it was wrong for the United States to be involved, not only for moral reasons but because we had not national interest in being involved.  It simply was not our fight, just as the Nigerian Civil War going on at the same time was not our fight.  I was also influenced by my parents who very  strongly opposed the Vietnam War.  They both had personal experience of war too.  My father was a WWII Army veteran and my mother lived in England during WWII.  Certainly my<br>
mother's stories from the perspective of a helpless civilian on the receiving end of enemy bombs had a powerful impact on me.<br><br>
My biggest problem personally during the Vietnam War was staying out of it.  Going to college of course gave me a student deferment which was fine as long as it lasted.  After four years, that was going to end naturally.  It happened that my graduation coincided with the first year of the Selective Service lottery in 1970.  I wound up with lottery number 161, which in that year was much to low to avoid the draft.  So., they called me for a physical which I passed.  By the way, I never saw such a group of young guys in terrible health.  Some were claiming to have diseases I'd never heard of.  By 1970, it seemed that very few people had any interest in going to war.  <br><br>
So, I was reclassified 1-A.  In response, I did two things: first, I appealed the reclassification on the grounds of hardship since I had a pregnant wife by that time, and second, we moved to Canada.  The appeal process dragged on until 1971 when the Appeals Board denied my application on a 3 - 0 vote.  However, since my reclassification became final in '71, I got into that year's lottery and the 161 didn't matter anymore.  I as lucky and got a high number the second time.  The job market in Canada wasn't very good so I returned to the U.S.  I've always wondered what I would have done if I had received an induction notice while living in Canada.  Would I have reported or not?  Actually, I probably would have as being a fugitive would have bothered me.  The point is that it would have been my choice whether or not to go.  I really have a problem with the draft as being a form of involuntary servitude (see the 13th Amendment).  It violates American ideals.  Ending the draft was maybe the only good thing to come out of the war.<br><br>
Incidentally, I found that Canadians had an ambivalent attitude to the American draft resisters who went up there. They weren't necessarily hostile but it wasn't something you<br>
would want to brag about.  It's odd because, like most of our allies (except for Australia and South Korea), Canada never got involved in Vietnam.  It's also interesting that in the early years of WWII, before Pearl Harbor, Canadians went south to avoid the draft.  
